\section{Survey of Social Movement Models}
\label{Survey_of_Social_Movement_Models/Survey of Social Movement Models:survey-of-social-movement-models}\label{Survey_of_Social_Movement_Models/Survey of Social Movement Models::doc}
This paper will survey the existing literature of simulation models of
social movements, reconstruct these models in the System Dynamics, Agent
Based Modeling, or other paradigms as appropriate, and simulate the
range of plausible behavioral outcomes these model reveal.

It will then group these models according to their structure, underlying
theory, and behavioral outcomes.


\subsection{Granovetter - Threshold Models of Collective Behavior}
\label{Survey_of_Social_Movement_Models/Granovetter_1978/Granovetter_1978::doc}\label{Survey_of_Social_Movement_Models/Granovetter_1978/Granovetter_1978:granovetter-threshold-models-of-collective-behavior}

Model based upon the paper: \href{http://www.jstor.org/stable/2094754}{http://www.jstor.org/stable/2094754}

\paragraph{Models of Crowds}
\label{Survey_of_Social_Movement_Models/Overview/Overview:models-of-crowds}
Models of crowds are a related but probably distinct type of modeling,
as they are interested not in the macrobehavior of movements over
timescales of weeks to years, but the behavior of groups of people on
the order of minutes to hours. It will probably be important to
understand how meaningful these distinctions are, and the similarities
between each type of model.
\begin{itemize}
\item {} 
Granovetter Threshold model

\end{itemize}


\paragraph{Narrative Models}
\label{Survey_of_Social_Movement_Models/Overview/Overview:narrative-models}
Based on our previous work, looking at the conflict between narrative
explainations of events within an individual.

\href{http://www.jstor.org/stable/2094754?seq=1\#page\_scan\_tab\_contents}{http://www.jstor.org/stable/2094754?seq=1\#page\_scan\_tab\_contents}

\section{Formalizing other social movement theories}
\label{Formal_Models_of_Other_Social_Movement_Theories/Formalizing_Theory::doc}\label{Formal_Models_of_Other_Social_Movement_Theories/Formalizing_Theory:formalizing-other-social-movement-theories}
This paper will formalize a variety of theories about the dynamic roots
of social movements as System Dynamics or Agent Based models drawn from
the traditional sociology literature. It will focus on theories that
have received less attention in the modeling literature. It will
categorize these models according to their theories and simulated
outcomes, in the context of the categories defined for models existing
in the literature.

\begin{Verbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
\PYGZsh{}The role of Stories

Thinking:
\PYGZhy{} Georges Sorel: Myth as essential for revolution
    Uncle Tom’s Cabin
    Paul Bloom: stories have helped shift the moral codes of nations
\end{Verbatim}

\section{Case Studies}
\label{Historical_Case_Studies/Case_Studies:case-studies}\label{Historical_Case_Studies/Case_Studies::doc}
These case studies should identify a major area of the social movement theory, identify which of the formalized models are appropriate for analyzing it, identify one or two cases in which this area is relevant, collect data about those components of the movement, and simulate the movement with data, in order to understand if the model is a good fit for the case.


\subsection{DDT and Silent Spring}
\label{Historical_Case_Studies/DDT/DDT:ddt-and-silent-spring}\label{Historical_Case_Studies/DDT/DDT::doc}
This case study looks at social movements which arise due to scientific
findings. DDT and Silent Spring is one aspect of this in practice, but
others exist:
\begin{itemize}
\item {} 
CFC bans

\item {} 
Leaded Gasoline, Lead paint Bans

\end{itemize}

Outline: - What is the history? Tell the story.


\subsection{Ending Apartheid in South Africa}
\label{Historical_Case_Studies/SA_Apartheid/SA_Apartheid:ending-apartheid-in-south-africa}\label{Historical_Case_Studies/SA_Apartheid/SA_Apartheid::doc}
This case study looks at divestment and the role of universities.

\section{Climate Movement}
\label{Models_of_the_Climate_Movement/Climate Movement::doc}\label{Models_of_the_Climate_Movement/Climate Movement:climate-movement}
How do committments from other countries influence political pressure
within a country to commit to reductions

If a perfect agreement is DOA because of the political situation back
home, what is the purpose of the summits? Must be to motivate political
change back home. What would a perfect agreement do to political
pressure? How would it change the conversation? Look to Kyoto?

\chapter{Stories}
\label{index:stories}
During this work, I hope to collect stories of individuals and groups that illustrate various components of the system, so that when the bulk of the thesis is complete, I can tell the same story – teach the same lessons – to a popular audience. Stories are the models of the mind, and so keeping a weather eye for stories that tell structure all the way through the research should facilitate this. Not only is the research likely to be a fertile ground for stories and storytelling, but if I am going to truly understand what I’m doing and have any authority on the subject, I need to be able to tell those stories.
